# PRACTICE: Styling text

In the HTML Exercises module we saw how to format text using `strong` and `em`.

Here we'll do the same, except we'll be styling a `span` element.

You know how `div` can be used to get together HTML elements that belong to the same group, creating a new block.

`span` is used to create an inline element (which means it does not alter the flow of the text.

To give a visual explanation, this is `div`:

![Screen Shot 2020-04-16 at 11.06.55.png](PRACTICE%20Styling%20text%201902767ad7e381c999d1f237f6fdacbc/Screen_Shot_2020-04-16_at_11.06.55.png)

This is `span`:

![Screen Shot 2020-04-16 at 11.07.05.png](PRACTICE%20Styling%20text%201902767ad7e381c999d1f237f6fdacbc/Screen_Shot_2020-04-16_at_11.07.05.png)

You don't even *see* there is a `span` element inside a paragraph.

But once it's there, you can style it:

```css
span {
  font-weight: bold;
}

```

![Screen Shot 2020-04-16 at 11.09.46.png](PRACTICE%20Styling%20text%201902767ad7e381c999d1f237f6fdacbc/Screen_Shot_2020-04-16_at_11.09.46.png)

```css
span {
  font-style: italic;
}

```

![Screen Shot 2020-04-16 at 11.10.31.png](PRACTICE%20Styling%20text%201902767ad7e381c999d1f237f6fdacbc/Screen_Shot_2020-04-16_at_11.10.31.png)

